1 Overall a pathetic and weak excuse for a Gyro.  The pita was slightly stale and chewy and there was so little meat here that it was lost in the pita, I feel cheated. The tzatziki sauce truly ruined it for me, it was unusually sweet and off putting, I've never tasted anything like it.
3 Had lunch here with my son and 2 friends yesterday. We had been wanting to try My Greek Corner for a while and finally got the chance! So we placed our order at the counter and were given our number to head off and get a table. The food is brought out pretty promptly which is nice.  One thing you should know about My Greek Corner is that you get a whole lotta food with your orders!  Each of us ordered a platter and got the main dish, a choice of two sides and what we came to know as a ridiculously large side-salad with our meals. That's a lot of food for lunch. Next time we know better. ;)  We ordered the hummus appetizer because what's a Greek place without hummus? The hummus was a little thin, but creamy and served with soft hot pita chips. It was adequate...nothing spectacular and lacked in garlic and other seasoning to kick up the chick pea factor.   We all selected roasted veggies for one of our side dishes and The roasted veggies are not roasted...they are steamed. They were past al-dente but not so far past that you felt geriatric. And the veggies could use a little seasoning on them--the seasoning from the fries would have been perfect.   The ridiculously oversized Greek salad wasn't really anything special. It looked nice as it had fresh crisp romaine, red onion slices and large chunks of feta, but the flavor was a bit bland. Each person got 1 kalamata olive each on our salad which we grinned about. The salad really is a meal in and of itself though and could be scaled back by almost 3/4 to really be considered a side salad.   My son had the falafel platter which came with 5 good size falafels, a side of non-roasted veggies, french fries, and a Greek Salad. The falafels were tasty and not hard as rocks like you get expect in some places. The seasoned fries were not over-salty which was nice. The salad was just too much though as it's size is a meal in and of itself.  My friend had the spanikopita platter which came with 1 spinach and 1 cheese spanikopita but hers came with 2 cheese. She chose fries and roasted veggies and along came that way oversized Greek Salad. She liked the spanikopita but wanted to try both flavors. Oh well maybe next time.  My other friend and I enjoyed the Gyro platters. She had the traditional lamb, and I had chicken. We both had rice and roasted vegetables and again that oversized Greek Salad. The rice was very bland. They made it in chicken broth so it had a yellow color to it leading you to believe it might be saffron rice...but no...it's plain white rice cooked in chicken broth. And if you are going to advertise ROASTED veggies, use the proper cooking technique.  As to the Gyros...they were tasty. The meat was thicker than you would expect which was actually a good thing. The tzatziki sauce was thick and flavorful. And again, the pitas were fresh and hot.   Overall, we liked My Greek Corner. It does have a drive thru, which is funny because you definitely can't eat very many of the menu offerings in the car. With a few tweaks, this place could definitely make it in the West Valley. People complain that it might be a bit expensive, but when you consider all the food you are getting for the price, it's actually quite reasonable and you certainly don't walk away feeling hungry! I definitely wouldn't consider this a fast food restaurant and I think people are mistaking it as such because it's housed in the former building where Fazoli's was.   I will definitely go back to My Greek Corner because I can't make it out to Doobie's Grill in Mesa as often as I'd like and Mike's Greek and Italian doesn't cut the mustard at all. Bottom line--go in with an open mind and you might be pleasantly surprised.
